gy">Scientology</a>&#160;</li>\n<li>&#160;<a href="/wiki/Portal:Shinto" title="Portal:Shinto">Shinto</a>&#160;</li>\n<li>&#160;<a href="/wiki/Portal:Theosophy" title="Portal:Theosophy">Theosophy</a>&#160;</li>\n<li>&#160;<a href="/wiki/Portal:Wicca" title="Portal:Wicca">Wicca</a>&#160;</li>\n<li>&#160;<a href="/wiki/Portal:Zoroastrianism" title="Portal:Zoroastrianism">Zoroastrianism</a>&#160;</li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n<center><b><i><font color="#004000"><big><big>T</big></big>he</font> <big><big>M</big></big>ahayana <big><big>B</big></big>uddhism <big><big>P</big></big>ortal</i></b></center>\n<div style="float:right; width:100%;">\n<hr />\n<table width="100%" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" border="0">\n<tr>\n<td style="padding:0 .3em; background-color:#ed9121; border:1px solid #FFA824; color: black; letter-spacing: 2px; word-spacing:3px; font-weight: bold; border-bottom:#FFC469&#160;; text-align:center; font-weight:bold;" width="32%"><i><a class="mw-selflink selflink">Main</a></i></td>\n<td style="background-color#FFC469; border-bottom:1px solid #FFC469" width="2%">&#160;</td>\n<td style="padding:0 .3em; background-color:#ed9121; border:1px solid #FFA824; color: black; letter-spacing: 2px; word-spacing:3px; font-weight: bold; border-bottom:#FFC469&#160;; text-align:center; font-weight:bold;" width="32%"><i><a href="/wiki/Portal:Mahayana_Buddhism/Tasks" title="Portal:Mahayana Buddhism/Tasks">Tasks</a></i></td>\n<td style="background-color#FFC469; border-bottom:1px solid #FFC469" width="2%">&#160;</td>\n<td style="padding:0 .3em; background-color:#ed9121; border:1px solid #FFA824; color: black; letter-spacing: 2px; word-spacing:3px; font-weight: bold; border-bottom:#FFC469&#160;; text-align:center; font-weight:bold;" width="32%"><i><a href="/wiki/Portal:Mahayana_Buddhism/Resources" title="Portal:Mahayana Buddhism/Resources">Resources</a></i></td>\n<td style="background-color#FFC469; border-bottom:1px solid #FFC469" width="2%">&#160;</td>\n</tr>\n</table>\n<table width="100%" cellpadding="5" cellspacing="10" style="background:#ed9121; border-style:solid; border-width:1px; border-color: ff8c00">\n<tr>\n<td style="vertical-align:top;padding: 0; margin:0;">\n<div style="clear: both; border: solid #ed9121; border-width: 1px 1px 0; background: #ffec8b; color: #8B0000; padding: .1em;padding-top: .1em;padding-left: .1em;padding-right: .1em;padding-bottom: .1em;text-align: center;font-family: sans-serif;font-size:100%;margin-bottom: 0px;">\n<div class="plainlinks" style="float:right;margin-bottom:.1em;font-size:80%; color: #8B0000"><a class="external text" href="//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Portal:Mahayana_Buddhism/Intro&amp;action=edit"><span style="color: #8B0000">edit</span></a>&#160;&#160;</div>\n<h2 style="font-family:sans-serif; font-size:100%; font-weight:bold; border: none; margin: 0; padding:0; padding-bottom:.1em; color:#8B0000;"><span class="mw-headline" id="Mahayana_Buddhism"><big>Mahayana Buddhism</big></span></h2>\n</div>\n<div style="border: 1px solid #ed9121; border-top-width: 1px; vertical-align: top;background: #ffec8b;opacity: 1; color: black; text-align: left; margin: 0 0 10px; padding: 1em;padding-top: .3em;">\n<div class="floatright"><a href="/wiki/File:Lotus_Nelumbo_nucifera_Flower_Large_3264px.jpg" class="image"><img alt="Lotus Nelumbo nucifera Flower Large 3264px.jpg" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/65/Lotus_Nelumbo_nucifera_Flower_Large_3264px.jpg/200px-Lotus_Nelumbo_nucifera_Flower_Large_3264px.jpg" width="200" height="150" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/65/Lotus_Nelumbo_nucifera_Flower_Large_3264px.jpg/300px-Lotus_Nelumbo_nucifera_Flower_Large_3264px.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/65/Lotus_Nelumbo_nucifera_Flower_Large_3264px.jpg/400px-Lotus_Nelumbo_nucifera_Flower_Large_3264px.jpg 2x" data-file-width="3264" data-file-height="2448" /></a></div>\nMah\xc4\x81y\xc4\x81na (<a href="/wiki/Sanskrit" title="Sanskrit">Sanskrit</a>: \xe0\xa4\xae\xe0\xa4\xb9\xe0\xa4\xbe\xe0\xa4\xaf\xe0\xa4\xbe\xe0\xa4\xa8, <i>mah\xc4\x81y\xc4\x81na</i>, literally the "Great Vehicle") is one of the two main existing branches of <a href="/wiki/Buddhism" title="Buddhism">Buddhism</a> and a term for classification of <a href="/wiki/Buddhist_philosophy" title="Buddhist philosophy">Buddhist philosophies</a> and practice. Mah\xc4\x81y\xc4\x81na Buddhism originated in <a href="/wiki/India" title="India">India</a>.\n<p>The Mah\xc4\x81y\xc4\x81na tradition is the larger of the two major traditions of Buddhism existing today, the other being that of the <a href="/wiki/Theravada" title="Theravada">Therav\xc4\x81da</a> school. According to the teachings of Mah\xc4\x81y\xc4\x81na traditions, "Mah\xc4\x81y\xc4\x81na" also refers to the path of seeking complete enlightenment for the benefit of all sentient beings, also called "Bodhisattvay\xc4\x81na", or the "<a href="/wiki/Bodhisattva" title="Bodhisattva">Bodhisattva</a> Vehicle."</p>\n<p>In the course of its history, Mah\xc4\x81y\xc4\x81na Buddhism spread from India to various other Asian countries such as <a href="/wiki/China" title="China">China</a>, <a href="/wiki/Japan" title="Japan">Japan</a>, <a href="/wiki/Vietnam" title="Vietnam">Vietnam</a>, <a href="/wiki/Korea" title="Korea">Korea</a>, <a href="/wiki/Singapore" title="Singapore">Singapore</a>, <a href="/wiki/Taiwan" title="Taiwan">Taiwan</a>, <a href="/wiki/Nepal" title="Nepal">Nepal</a>, <a href="/wiki/Tibet" title="Tibet">Tibet</a>, <a href="/wiki/Bhutan" title="Bhutan">Bhutan</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Mongolia" title="Mongolia">Mongolia</a>. Major traditions of Mah\xc4\x81y\xc4\x81na Buddhism today include <a href="/wiki/Zen" title="Zen">Zen/Ch\xc3\xa1n</a>, <a href="/wiki/Pure_Land_Buddhism" title="Pure Land Buddhism">Pure Land</a>, <a href="/wiki/Tiantai" title="Tiantai">Tiantai</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Nichiren_Buddhism" title="Nichiren Buddhism">Nichiren</a>, as well as the <a href="/wiki/Esoteric_Buddhism" class="mw-redirect" title="Esoteric Buddhism">Esoteric Buddhist</a> traditions of <a href="/wiki/Shingon" class="mw-redirect" title="Shingon">Shingon</a> and <a href="/wiki/Tibetan_Buddhism" title="Tibetan Buddhism">Tibetan Buddhism</a>.</p>\n<div class="noprint" style="margin:0.3em 0.2em 0.2em 0.3em; padding:0.3em 0.2em 0.2em 0.3em; text-align:right;"><b><a href="/wiki/Mahayana_Buddhism" class="mw-redirect" title="Mahayana Buddhism">Learn more about Mahayana Buddhism...</a></b></div>\n<div style="clear:both;"></div>\n</div>\n<p><br /></p>\n<div class="portal-column-right">\n<div style="clear: both; border: solid #ed9121; border-width: 1px 1px 0; background: #ffec8b; color: #8B0000; padding: .1em;padding-top: .1em;padding-left: .1em;padding-right: .1em;padding-bottom: .1em;text-align: center;font-family: sans-serif;font-size:100%;margin-bottom: 0px;">\n<div class="plainlinks" style="float:right;margin-bottom:.1em;font-size:80%; color: #8B0000"><a class="external text" href="//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Portal:Mahayana_Buddhism/Selected_Mahayana_Buddhist&amp;action=edit"><span style="color: #8B0000">edit</span></a>&#160;&#160;</div>\n<h2 style="font-family:sans-serif; font-size:100%; font-weight:bold; border: none; margin: 0; padding:0; padding-bottom:.1em; color:#8B0000;"><span class="mw-headline" id="Selected_Mahayana_Buddhist">Selected Mahayana Buddhist</span></h2>\n</div>\n<div style="border: 1px solid #ed9121; border-top-width: 1px; vertical-align: top;background: #ffec8b;opacity: 1; color: black; text-align: left; margin: 0 0 10px; padding: 1em;padding-top: .3em;">\n<div class="floatleft"><a href="/wiki/File:Nagarjuna.gif" class="image"><img alt="Nagarjuna.gif" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/bb/Nagarjuna.gif/110px-Nagarjuna.gif" width="110" height="124" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/bb/Nagarjuna.gif/165px-Nagarjuna.gif 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/bb/Nagarjuna.gif/220px-Nagarjuna.gif 2x" data-file-width="300" data-file-height="339" /></a></div>\n<p><b>Acharya N\xc4\x81g\xc4\x81rjuna</b> (<a href="/wiki/Telugu_script" title="Telugu script">Telugu</a>: \xe0\xb0\xa8\xe0\xb0\xbe\xe0\xb0\x97\xe0\xb0\xbe\xe0\xb0\xb0\xe0\xb1\x8d\xe0\xb0\x9c\xe0\xb1\x81\xe0\xb0\xa8; <a href="/wiki/Chinese_language" title="Chinese language">Chinese</a>: \xe9\xbe\x8d\xe6\xa8\xb9; <a href="/wiki/Tibetan_language" class="mw-disambig" title="Tibetan language">Tibetan</a><sup class="plainlinks noprint Inline-Template" style="vertical-align:text-top;white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://dispenser.homenet.org/~dispenser/cgi-bin/dab_solver.py?page=Portal:Mahayana_Buddhism&amp;editintro=Template:Disambiguation_needed/editintro&amp;client=Template:Dn"><span title="Link needs disambiguation. (July 2017)">disambiguation needed</span></a></i>]</sup>: <i>Klu Sgrub</i>) (c. <a href="/wiki/150" title="150">150</a> - <a href="/wiki/250" title="250">250</a> <a href="/wiki/Common_Era" title="Common Era">CE</a>) was an <a href="/wiki/India" title="India">Indian</a> philosopher, the founder of the <a href="/wiki/Madhyamaka" title="Madhyamaka">Madhyamaka</a> (Middle Path) school of <a href="/wiki/Mah%C4%81y%C4%81na" class="mw-redirect" title="Mah\xc4\x81y\xc4\x81na">Mah\xc4\x81y\xc4\x81na</a> <a href="/wiki/Buddhism" title="Buddhism">Buddhism</a>, and arguably the most influential Buddhist thinker after <a href="/wiki/Gautama_Buddha" title="Gautama Buddha">Gautama Buddha</a> himself.</p>\n<p>His writings were the basis for the formation of the Madhyamaka (Middle Way) school, which was transmitted to China under the name of the Three Treatise (<a href="/wiki/Sanlun" class="mw-redirect" title="Sanlun">Sanlun</a>) School. He is credited with developing the philosophy of the <a href="/wiki/Prajnaparamita" title="Prajnaparamita">Prajnaparamita</a> <a href="/wiki/Sutra" title="Sutra">sutras</a>, and was closely associated with the Buddhist university of <a href="/wiki/Nalanda" title="Nalanda">Nalanda</a>. In the <a href="/wiki/Jodo_Shinshu" class="mw-redirect" title="Jodo Shinshu">Jodo Shinshu</a> branch of Buddhism, he is considered the First <a href="/wiki/Jodo_Shinshu_Patriarchs" class="mw-redirect" title="Jodo Shinshu Patriarchs">Patriarch</a>.</p>\n<p>Little is known about the actual life of the historical Nagarjuna. The two most extensive biographies of Nagarjuna, one in Chinese and the other in Tibetan, were written many centuries after his life and incorporate much lively but historically unreliable material which sometimes reaches mythic proportions. Nagarjuna was born a <a href="/wiki/Brahmin" title="Brahmin">Brahmin</a>, which in his time connoted religious allegiance to the Vedas, probably into an upper-caste Brahmin family and probably in the southern Andhra region of India<a rel="nofollow" class="external autonumber" href="http://www.iep.utm.edu/n/nagarjun.htm#H1">[1]</a>.</p>\n<div class="noprint" style="margin:0.3em 0.2em 0.2em 0.3em; padding:0.3em 0.2em 0.2em 0.3em; text-align:right;"><b><a href="/wiki/Nagarjuna" title="Nagarjuna">Read more...</a></b></div>\n<div style="clear:both;"></div>\n</div>\n<div style="clear: both; border: solid #ed9121; border-width: 1px 1px 0; background: #ffec8b; color: #8B0000; padding: .1em;padding-top: .1em;padding-left: .1em;padding-right: .1em;padding-bottom: .1em;text-align: center;font-family: sans-serif;font-size:100%;margin-bottom: 0px;">\n<div class="plainlinks" style="float:right;margin-bottom:.1em;font-size:80%; color: #8B0000"><a class="external text" href="//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Portal:Mahayana_Buddhism/Selected_Buddha/Bodhisattva&amp;action=edit"><span style="color: #8B0000">edit</span></a>&#160;&#160;</div>\n<h2 style="font-family:sans-serif; font-size:100%; font-weight:bold; border: none; margin: 0; padding:0; padding-bottom:.1em; color:#8B0000;"><span class="mw-headline" id="Selected_Buddha.2FBodhisattva">Selected Buddha/Bodhisattva</span></h2>\n</div>\n<div style="border: 1px solid #ed9121; border-top-width: 1px; vertical-align: top;background: #ffec8b;opacity: 1; color: black; text-align: left; margin: 0 0 10px; padding: 1em;padding-top: .3em;">\n<div class="floatright"><a href="/wiki/File:Manjushri_japan.jpg" class="image"><img alt="Manjushri japan.jpg" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c9/Manjushri_japan.jpg/100px-Manjushri_japan.jpg" width="100" height="133" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c9/Manjushri_japan.jpg/150px-Manjushri_japan.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c9/Manjushri_japan.jpg/200px-Manjushri_japan.jpg 2x" data-file-width="450" data-file-height="600" /></a></div>\n<p>Manjusri (Ch: \xe6\x96\x87\xe6\xae\x8a W\xc3\xa9nsh\xc5\xab or \xe6\x96\x87\xe6\xae\x8a\xe5\xb8\xab\xe5\x88\xa9\xe8\x8f\xa9\xe8\x96\xa9 W\xc3\xa9nsh\xc5\xabshili P\xc3\xbas\xc3\xa0; Jp: Monju; Tib: Jampelyang; <a href="/wiki/Nepali_language" title="Nepali language">Nepalese</a>: \xe0\xa4\xae\xe0\xa4\x82\xe0\xa4\x9c\xe0\xa5\x81\xe0\xa4\xb6\xe0\xa5\x8d\xe0\xa4\xb0\xe0\xa5\x80 Manjushree) is a <a href="/wiki/Bodhisattva" title="Bodhisattva">bodhisattva</a> in the <a href="/wiki/Mahayana" title="Mahayana">Mahayana</a> and <a href="/wiki/Vajrayana" title="Vajrayana">Vajrayana</a> traditions of <a href="/wiki/Buddhism" title="Buddhism">Buddhism</a>, and is considered a <a href="/wiki/Yidam" title="Yidam">yidam</a>, or titular deity in <a href="/wiki/Tibetan_Buddhism" title="Tibetan Buddhism">Tibetan Buddhism</a> specifically. Manjusri is the bodhisattva associated with wisdom, doctrine and awareness. Historically, Manjusri was a disciple of the <a href="/wiki/Buddha" class="mw-redirect" title="Buddha">Buddha</a>. Interestingly, it is the origin of the ethnonym Manchu.</p>\n<p>The <a href="/wiki/Sanskrit" title="Sanskrit">Sanskrit</a> term Ma\xc3\xb1ju\xc5\x9br\xc4\xab can be translated as "Gentle Glory". Ma\xc3\xb1ju\xc5\x9br\xc4\xab is also known by the fuller Sanskrit name of Ma\xc3\xb1ju\xc5\x9br\xc4\xab-kum\xc4\x81ra-bh\xc5\xabta.</p>\n<div class="noprint" style="margin:0.3em 0.2em 0.2em 0.3em; padding:0.3em 0.2em 0.2em 0.3em; text-align:right;"><b><a href="/wiki/Manjusri" class="mw-redirect" title="Manjusri">Read more...</a></b></div>\n<div style="clear:both;"></div>\n</div>\n<div style="clear: both; border: solid #ed9121; border-width: 1px 1px 0; background: #ffec8b; color: #8B0000; padding: .1em;padding-top: .1em;padding-left: .1em;padding-right: .1em;padding-bottom: .1em;text-align: center;font-family: sans-serif;font-size:100%;margin-bottom: 0px;">\n<div class="plainlinks" style="float:right;margin-bottom:.1em;font-size:80%; color: #8B0000"><a class="external text" href="//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Portal:Mahayana_Buddhism/Selected_Scripture&amp;action=edit"><span style="color: #8B0000">edit</span></a>&#160;&#160;</div>\n<h2 style="font-family:sans-serif; font-size:100%; font-weight:bold; border: none; margin: 0; padding:0; padding-bottom:.1em; color:#8B0000;"><span class="mw-headline" id="Selected_Scripture">Selected Scripture</span></h2>\n</div>\n<div style="border: 1px solid #ed9121; border-top-width: 1px; vertical-align: top;background: #ffec8b;opacity: 1; color: black; text-align: left; margin: 0 0 10px; padding: 1em;padding-top: .3em;">\n<p>The Heart of Perfect Wisdom Sutra or <a href="/wiki/Heart_Sutra" title="Heart Sutra">Heart Sutra</a> or Essence of Wisdom Sutra (<a href="/wiki/Sanskrit" title="Sanskrit">Sanskrit</a>: \xe0\xa4\xaa\xe0\xa5\x8d\xe0\xa4\xb0\xe0\xa4\x9c\xe0\xa5\x8d\xe0\xa4\x9e\xe0\xa4\xbe\xe0\xa4\xaa\xe0\xa4\xbe\xe0\xa4\xb0\xe0\xa4\xae\xe0\xa4\xbf\xe0\xa4\xa4\xe0\xa4\xbe\xe0\xa4\xb9\xe0\xa5\x83\xe0\xa4\xa6\xe0\xa4\xaf\xe0\xa4\xb8\xe0\xa5\x82\xe0\xa4\xa4\xe0\xa5\x8d\xe0\xa4\xb0 Praj\xc3\xb1\xc4\x81p\xc4\x81ramit\xc4\x81 H\xe1\xb9\x9bdaya S\xc5\xabtra; traditional <a href="/wiki/Chinese_language" title="Chinese language">Chinese</a>: \xe8\x88\xac\xe8\x8b\xa5\xe6\xb3\xa2\xe7\xbe\x85\xe8\x9c\x9c\xe5\xa4\x9a\xe5\xbf\x83\xe7\xb6\x93, <a href="/wiki/Pinyin" title="Pinyin">Pinyin</a>: B\xc5\x8dr\xc4\x95b\xc5\x8dlu\xc3\xb3m\xc3\xacdu\xc5\x8d X\xc4\xabnj\xc4\xabng; [[Japanese]: \xe6\x91\xa9\xe8\xa8\xb6\xe8\x88\xac\xe8\x8b\xa5\xe6\xb3\xa2\xe7\xbe\x85\xe8\x9c\x9c\xe5\xa4\x9a\xe5\xbf\x83\xe7\xb5\x8c, Maka Hannyaharamita Shingy\xc5\x8d; <a href="/wiki/Korean_language" title="Korean language">Korean</a>: \xeb\xb0\x98\xec\x95\xbc\xec\x8b\xac\xea\xb2\xbd, Banya Simgyeong, <a href="/wiki/Vietnamese_language" title="Vietnamese language">Vietnamese</a>: B\xc3\xa1t Nh\xc3\xa3 Ba La M\xe1\xba\xadt \xc4\x90a T\xc3\xa2m Kinh) (<a href="/wiki/Standard_Tibetan" title="Standard Tibetan">Tibetan</a>: sNying mDo or shes rab snying po\'i mdo) is a well-known <a href="/wiki/Mah%C4%81y%C4%81na" class="mw-redirect" title="Mah\xc4\x81y\xc4\x81na">Mah\xc4\x81y\xc4\x81na</a> <a href="/wiki/Buddhist" class="mw-redirect" title="Buddhist">Buddhist</a> <a href="/wiki/Sutra" title="Sutra">sutra</a> that is very popular among Mahayana Buddhists both for its brevity and depth of meaning.</p>\n<div class="noprint" style="margin:0.3em 0.2em 0.2em 0.3em; padding:0.3em 0.2em 0.2em 0.3em; text-align:right;"><b><a href="/wiki/Heart_Sutra" title="Heart Sutra">Read more...</a></b></div>\n<div style="clear:both;"></div>\n</div>\n<div style="clear: both; border: solid #ed9121; border-width: 1px 1px 0; background: #ffec8b; color: #8B0000; padding: .1em;padding-top: .1em;padding-left: .1em;padding-right: .1em;padding-bottom: .1em;text-align: center;font-family: sans-serif;font-size:100%;margin-bottom: 0px;">\n<div class="plainlinks" style="float:right;margin-bottom:.1em;font-size:80%; color: #8B0000"><a class="external text" href="//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Portal:Mahayana_Buddhism/Selected_Mahayana_Practice&amp;action=edit"><span style="color: #8B0000">edit</span></a>&#160;&#160;</div>\n<h2 style="font-family:sans-serif; font-size:100%; font-weight:bold; border: none; margin: 0; padding:0; padding-bottom:.1em; color:#8B0000;"><span class="mw-headline" id="Selected_Mahayana_Practice">Selected Mahayana Practice</span></h2>\n</div>\n<div style="border: 1px solid #ed9121; border-top-width: 1px; vertical-align: top;background: #ffec8b;opacity: 1; color: black; text-align: left; margin: 0 0 10px; padding: 1em;padding-top: .3em;">\n<p><a href="/wiki/Buddhist" class="mw-redirect" title="Buddhist">Buddhist</a> meditation encompasses a variety of <a href="/wiki/Meditation" title="Meditation">meditation</a> techniques that develop mindfulness, concentration, tranquility and insight. Core meditation techniques are preserved in ancient <a href="/wiki/Buddhist_texts" title="Buddhist texts">Buddhist texts</a> and have proliferated and diversified through the millennia of teacher-student transmissions.</p>\n<p>Non-Buddhists use these techniques for the pursuit of physical and mental health as well as for non-Buddhist spiritual aims. Buddhists pursue meditation as part of the path toward <a href="/wiki/Enlightenment_(spiritual)" title="Enlightenment (spiritual)">Enlightenment</a> and <a href="/wiki/Nirvana_(concept)" class="mw-redirect" title="Nirvana (concept)">Nirvana</a>.</p>\n<p>The closest words for meditation in the classical languages of Buddhism are bh\xc4\x81van\xc4\x81 and jh\xc4\x81na (P\xc4\x81li; Skt.: <a href="/wiki/Dhy%C4%81na_in_Buddhism" title="Dhy\xc4\x81na in Buddhism">dhy\xc4\x81na</a>).[4]</p>\n<p>Given the large number and diversity of traditional Buddhist meditation practices, this article primarily identifies authoritative contextual frameworks \xe2\x80\x93 both contemporary and canonical \xe2\x80\x93 for the variety of practices. For those seeking school-specific meditation instruction, it might be most expedient to simply review articles listed in the "See also" section below.</p>\n<div class="noprint" style="margin:0.3em 0.2em 0.2em 0.3em; padding:0.3em 0.2em 0.2em 0.3em; text-align:right;"><b><a href="/wiki/Buddhist_Meditation" class="mw-redirect" title="Buddhist Meditation">Read more...</a></b></div>\n<div style="clear:both;"></div>\n</div>\n<div style="clear: both; border: solid #ed9121; border-width: 1px 1px 0; background: #ffec8b; color: #8B0000; padding: .1em;padding-top: .1em;padding-left: .1em;padding-right: .1em;padding-bottom: .1em;text-align: center;font-family: sans-serif;font-size:100%;margin-bottom: 0px;">\n<div class="plainlinks" style="float:right;margin-bottom:.1em;font-size:80%; color: #8B0000"><a class="external text" href="//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Portal:Mahayana_Buddhism/Selected_Artwork&amp;action=edit"><span style="color: #8B0000">edit</span></a>&#160;&#160;</div>\n<h2 style="font-family:sans-serif; font-size:100%; font-weight:bold; border: none; margin: 0; padding:0; padding-bottom:.1em; color:#8B0000;"><span class="mw-headline" id="Selected_Artwork">Selected Artwork</span></h2>\n</div>\n<div style="border: 1px solid #ed9121; border-top-width: 1px; vertical-align: top;background: #ffec8b;opacity: 1; color: black; text-align: left; margin: 0 0 10px; padding: 1em;padding-top: .3em;">\n<div class="center">\n<div class="floatnone"><a href="/wiki/File:Liao_Dynasty_-_Guan_Yin_statue.jpg" class="image"><img alt="Liao Dynasty - Guan Yin statue.jpg" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/0f/Liao_Dynasty_-_Guan_Yin_statue.jpg/200px-Liao_Dynasty_-_Guan_Yin_statue.jpg" width="200" height="267" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/0f/Liao_Dynasty_-_Guan_Yin_statue.jpg/300px-Liao_Dynasty_-_Guan_Yin_statue.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/0f/Liao_Dynasty_-_Guan_Yin_statue.jpg/400px-Liao_Dynasty_-_Guan_Yin_statue.jpg 2x" data-file-width="960" data-file-height="1280" /></a></div>\n</div>\n<div class="noprint" style="margin:0.3em 0.2em 0.2em 0.3em; padding:0.3em 0.2em 0.2em 0.3em; text-align:right;"></div>\n<div style="clear:both;"></div>\n</div>\n<div style="clear: both; border: solid #ed9121; border-width: 1px 1px 0; background: #ffec8b; color: #8B0000; padding: .1em;padding-top: .1em;padding-left: .1em;padding-right: .1em;padding-bottom: .1em;text-align: center;font-family: sans-serif;font-size:100%;margin-bottom: 0px;">\n<div class="plainlinks" style="float:right;margin-bottom:.1em;font-size:80%; color: #8B0000"><a class="external text" href="//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Portal:Mahayana_Buddhism/Did_You_Know%3F&amp;action=edit"><span style="color: #8B0000">edit</span></a>&#160;&#160;</div>\n<h2 style="font-family:sans-serif; font-size:100%; font-weight:bold; border: none; margin: 0; padding:0; padding-bottom:.1em; color:#8B0000;"><span class="mw-headline" id="Did_You_Know.3F">Did You Know?</span></h2>\n</div>\n<div style="border: 1px solid #ed9121; border-top-width: 1px; vertical-align: top;background: #ffec8b;opacity: 1; color: black; text-align: left; margin: 0 0 10px; padding: 1em;padding-top: .3em;">\n<ul>\n<li><a href="/wiki/Ashvagosha" class="mw-redirect" title="Ashvagosha">Ashvagosha</a>, the first <a href="/wiki/Sanskrit" title="Sanskrit">Sanskrit</a> dramatist, was advisor to the <a href="/wiki/Buddhist" class="mw-redirect" title="Buddhist">Buddhist</a> king, <a href="/wiki/Kanishka" title="Kanishka">Kanishka</a>.</li>\n<li><a href="/wiki/Zen" title="Zen">Zen</a> was brought to <a href="/wiki/Japanese_Buddhism" class="mw-redirect" title="Japanese Buddhism">Japan</a> in the late 12th century, by the monk <a href="/wiki/Eisai" title="Eisai">Eisai</a>.</li>\n</ul>\n<div class="noprint" style="margin:0.3em 0.2em 0.2em 0.3em; padding:0.3em 0.2em 0.2em 0.3em; text-align:right;"></div>\n<div style="clear:both;"></div>\n</div>\n<p><br /></p>\n</div>\n<div class="portal-column-left">\n<div style="clear: both; border: solid #ed9121; border-width: 1px 1px 0; background: #ffec8b; color: #8B0000; padding: .1em;padding-top: .1em;padding-left: .1em;padding-right: .1em;padding-bottom: .1em;text-align: center;font-family: sans-serif;font-size:100%;margin-bottom: 0px;">\n<div class="plainlinks" style="float:right;margin-bottom:.1em;font-size:80%; color: #8B0000"><a class="external text" href="//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Portal:Mahayana_Buddhism/Selected_Article&amp;action=edit"><span style="color: #8B0000">edit</span></a>&#160;&#160;</div>\n<h2 style="font-family:sans-serif; font-size:100%; font-weight:bold; border: none; margin: 0; padding:0; padding-bottom:.1em; color:#8B0000;"><span class="mw-headline" id="Selected_Article">Selected Article</span></h2>\n</div>\n<div style="border: 1px solid #ed9121; border-top-width: 1px; vertical-align: top;background: #ffec8b;opacity: 1; color: black; text-align: left; margin: 0 0 10px; padding: 1em;padding-top: .3em;">\n<div class="floatright"><a href="/wiki/File:Jingangjing.jpg" class="image"><img alt="Jingangjing.jpg" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d2/Jingangjing.jpg/200px-Jingangjing.jpg" width="200" height="140" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d2/Jingangjing.jpg/300px-Jingangjing.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d2/Jingangjing.jpg/400px-Jingangjing.jpg 2x" data-file-width="4917" data-file-height="3438" /></a></div>\n<p>The <b>Diamond Sutra</b> (<a href="/wiki/Sanskrit" title="Sanskrit">Sanskrit</a>: \xe0\xa4\xb5\xe0\xa4\x9c\xe0\xa5\x8d\xe0\xa4\xb0\xe0\xa4\x9a\xe0\xa5\x8d\xe0\xa4\x9b\xe0\xa5\x87\xe0\xa4\xa6\xe0\xa4\xbf\xe0\xa4\x95\xe0\xa4\xbe \xe0\xa4\xaa\xe0\xa5\x8d\xe0\xa4\xb0\xe0\xa4\x9c\xe0\xa5\x8d\xe0\xa4\x9e\xe0\xa4\xbe\xe0\xa4\xaa\xe0\xa4\xbe\xe0\xa4\xb0\xe0\xa4\xae\xe0\xa4\xbf\xe0\xa4\xa4\xe0\xa4\xbe\xe0\xa4\xb8\xe0\xa5\x82\xe0\xa4\xa4\xe0\xa5\x8d\xe0\xa4\xb0 <i>Vajracchedik\xc4\x81-praj\xc3\xb1\xc4\x81p\xc4\x81ramit\xc4\x81-s\xc5\xabtra</i>; <a href="/wiki/Chinese_language" title="Chinese language">Chinese</a>: \xe9\x87\x91\xe5\x89\x9b\xe8\x88\xac\xe8\x8b\xa5\xe6\xb3\xa2\xe7\xbe\x85\xe8\x9c\x9c\xe5\xa4\x9a\xe7\xb6\x93 or short \xe9\x87\x91\xe5\x89\x9b\xe7\xb6\x93, <a href="/wiki/Pinyin" title="Pinyin">pinyin</a>: <i>j\xc4\xabng\xc4\x81ng b\xc5\x8dr\xc4\x9b b\xc5\x8dlu\xc3\xb3m\xc3\xacdu\xc5\x8d j\xc4\xabng</i> or <i>j\xc4\xabng\xc4\x81ng j\xc4\xabng</i>; <a href="/wiki/Japanese_language" title="Japanese language">Japanese</a>: <i>kongou hannya haramita kyou</i> or short <i>kongou kyou</i>; <a href="/wiki/Korean_language" title="Korean language">Korean</a>: \xea\xb8\x88\xea\xb0\x95\xeb\xb0\x98\xec\x95\xbc\xeb\xb0\x94\xeb\x9d\xbc\xeb\xb0\x80\xea\xb2\xbd (\xe9\x87\x91\xe5\x89\x9b\xe8\x88\xac\xe8\x8b\xa5\xe6\xb3\xa2\xe7\xbe\x85\xe8\x9c\x9c\xe7\xb6\x93), or \xea\xb8\x88\xea\xb0\x95\xea\xb2\xbd (\xe9\x87\x91\xe5\x89\x9b\xe7\xb6\x93) for short; <a href="/wiki/Vietnamese_language" title="Vietnamese language">Vietnamese</a> <i>Kim c\xc6\xb0\xc6\xa1ng b\xc3\xa1t-nh\xc3\xa3-ba-la-m\xe1\xba\xadt-\xc4\x91a kinh</i> or <i>Kim c\xc6\xb0\xc6\xa1ng kinh</i>; <a href="/wiki/Classical_Tibetan" title="Classical Tibetan">Tibetan</a> (<a href="/wiki/Wylie_transliteration" title="Wylie transliteration">Wylie</a>): <i>\xe2\x80\x99Phags pa shes rab kyi pha rol tu phyin pa rdo rje gcod pa zhes bya ba theg pa chen po\xe2\x80\x99i mdo</i>; "The Sutra of the Perfection of Wisdom of the Diamond that Cuts Through Illusion") is a short <a href="/wiki/Mahayana" title="Mahayana">Mahayana</a> <a href="/wiki/Sutra" title="Sutra">sutra</a> of the <a href="/wiki/Perfection_of_Wisdom" class="mw-redirect" title="Perfection of Wisdom">Perfection of Wisdom</a> genre, which teaches the practice of the avoidance of abiding in extremes of mental attachment. A copy of the Diamond Sutra, found sealed in a cave in <a href="/wiki/China" title="China">China</a> in the early 20th century, is the oldest known printed <a href="/wiki/Book" title="Book">book</a>, with a date of 868.<sup id="cite_ref-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-1">[1]</a></sup></p>\n<div class="noprint" style="margin:0.3em 0.2em 0.2em 0.3em; padding:0.3em 0.2em 0.2em 0.3em; text-align:right;"><b><a href="/wiki/Diamond_Sutra" title="Diamond Sutra">Read more...</a></b></div>\n<div style="clear:both;"></div>\n</div>\n<div style="clear: both; border: solid #ed9121; border-width: 1px 1px 0; background: #ffec8b; color: #8B0000; padding: .1em;padding-top: .1em;padding-left: .1em;padding-right: .1em;padding-bottom: .1em;text-align: center;font-family: sans-serif;font-size:100%;margin-bottom: 0px;">\n<div class="plainlinks" style="float:right;margin-bottom:.1em;font-size:80%; color: #8B0000"><a class="external text" href="//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Portal:Mahayana_Buddhism/Selected_Picture&amp;action=edit"><span style="color: #8B0000">edit</span></a>&#160;&#160;</div>\n<h2 style="font-family:sans-serif; font-size:100%; font-weight:bold; border: none; margin: 0; padding:0; padding-bottom:.1em; color:#8B0000;"><span class="mw-headline" id="Selected_Picture">Selected Picture</span></h2>\n</div>\n<div style="border: 1px solid #ed9121; border-top-width: 1px; vertical-align: top;background: #ffec8b;opacity: 1; color: black; text-align: left; margin: 0 0 10px; padding: 1em;padding-top: .3em;">\n<div class="center">\n<div class="floatnone"><a href="/wiki/File:Luohan_side.jpg" class="image"><img alt="Luohan side.jpg" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d1/Luohan_side.jpg/350px-Luohan_side.jpg" width="350" height="359" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/d/d1/Luohan_side.jpg 1.5x" data-file-width="487" data-file-height="500" /></a></div>\n</div>\n<p><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Featured_pictures" title="Wikipedia:Featured pictures">More featured pictures...</a></p>\n<div class="noprint" style="margin:0.3em 0.2em 0.2em 0.3em; padding:0.3em 0.2em 0.2em 0.3em; text-align:right;"></div>\n<div style="clear:both;"></div>\n</div>\n<div style="clear: both; border: solid #ed9121; border-width: 1px 1px 0; background: #ffec8b; color: #8B0000; padding: .1em;padding-top: .1em;padding-left: .1em;padding-right: .1em;padding-bottom: .1em;text-align: center;font-family: sans-serif;font-size:100%;margin-bottom: 0px;">\n<div class="plainlinks" style="float:right;margin-bottom:.1em;font-size:80%; color: #8B0000"><a class="external text" href="//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Portal:Mahayana_Buddhism/Selected_Quote&amp;action=edit"><span style="color: #8B0000">edit</span></a>&#160;&#160;</div>\n<h2 style="font-family:sans-serif; font-size:100%; font-weight:bold; border: none; margin: 0; padding:0; padding-bottom:.1em; color:#8B0000;"><span class="mw-headline" id="Selected_Quote">Selected Quote</span></h2>\n</div>\n<div style="border: 1px solid #ed9121; border-top-width: 1px; vertical-align: top;background: #ffec8b;opacity: 1; color: black; text-align: left; margin: 0 0 10px; padding: 1em;padding-top: .3em;">\n<p><i>If, Mahamati, you say that because of the reality of words the objects are, this talk lacks in sense. Words are not known in all the Buddha-lands; words, Mahamati, are an artificial creation. In some Buddha-lands ideas are indicated by looking steadily, in others by gestures, in still others by a frown, by the movement of the eyes, by laughing, by yawning, or by the clearing of the throat, or by recollection, or by trembling</i> - <a href="/wiki/Lankavatara_Sutra" class="mw-redirect" title="Lankavatara Sutra">Lankavatara Sutra</a></p>\n<div class="noprint" style="margin:0.3em 0.2em 0.2em 0.3em; padding:0.3em 0.2em 0.2em 0.3em; text-align:right;"></div>\n<div style="clear:both;"></div>\n</div>\n<div style="clear: both; border: solid #ed9121; border-width: 1px 1px 0; background: #ffec8b; color: #8B0000; padding: .1em;padding-top: .1em;padding-left: .1em;padding-right: .1em;padding-bottom: .1em;text-align: center;font-family: sans-serif;font-size:100%;margin-bottom: 0px;">\n<div class="plainlinks" style="float:right;margin-bottom:.1em;font-size:80%; color: #8B0000"><a class="external text" href="//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Portal:Mahayana_Buddhism/Selected_School&amp;action=edit"><span style="color: #8B0000">edit</span></a>&#160;&#160;</div>\n<h2 style="font-family:sans-serif; font-size:100%; font-weight:bold; border: none; margin: 0; padding:0; padding-bottom:.1em; color:#8B0000;"><span class="mw-headline" id="Selected_School">Selected School</span></h2>\n</div>\n<div style="border: 1px solid #ed9121; border-top-width: 1px; vertical-align: top;background: #ffec8b;opacity: 1; color: black; text-align: left; margin: 0 0 10px; padding: 1em;padding-top: .3em;">\n<div class="floatright"><a href="/wiki/File:Enso2.png" class="image"><img alt="Enso2.png" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/0f/Enso2.png/100px-Enso2.png" width="100" height="99" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/0f/Enso2.png/150px-Enso2.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/0f/Enso2.png/200px-Enso2.png 2x" data-file-width="246" data-file-height="244" /></a></div>\n<p>Zen (Japanese: \xe7\xa6\x85) also known as Ch\xc3\xa1n (Chinese: \xe7\xa6\x85) (see lengthy etymology below) is a school of <a href="/wiki/Mah%C4%81y%C4%81na" class="mw-redirect" title="Mah\xc4\x81y\xc4\x81na">Mah\xc4\x81y\xc4\x81na</a> Buddhism notable for its emphasis on mindful acceptance of the present moment, spontaneous action, and letting go of self-conscious and judgmental thinking.</p>\n<p>It emphasizes <a href="/wiki/Dharma" title="Dharma">dharma</a> practice and experiential wisdom\xe2\x80\x94particularly as realized in the form of <a href="/wiki/Meditation" title="Meditation">meditation</a> known as <a href="/wiki/Zazen" title="Zazen">zazen</a>\xe2\x80\x94in the attainment of awakening. As such, it de-emphasizes both theoretical knowledge and the study of religious texts in favor of direct individual experience of one\'s own experience.</p>\n<p>A broader term is the <a href="/wiki/Sanskrit" title="Sanskrit">Sanskrit</a> word "<a href="/wiki/Dhy%C4%81na_in_Buddhism" title="Dhy\xc4\x81na in Buddhism">dhyana</a>", which exists also in other religions in <a href="/wiki/India" title="India">India</a>.</p>\n<p>The emergence of Ch\xc3\xa1n (Zen) as a distinct school of <a href="/wiki/Buddhism" title="Buddhism">Buddhism</a> was first documented in <a href="/wiki/Chinese_Buddhism" title="Chinese Buddhism">China</a> in the 7th century CE. It is thought to have developed as an amalgam of various currents in Mah\xc4\x81y\xc4\x81na <a href="/wiki/Buddhist" class="mw-redirect" title="Buddhist">Buddhist</a> thought\xe2\x80\x94among them the <a href="/wiki/Yog%C4%81c%C4%81ra" class="mw-redirect" title="Yog\xc4\x81c\xc4\x81ra">Yog\xc4\x81c\xc4\x81ra</a> and <a href="/wiki/Madhyamaka" title="Madhyamaka">Madhyamaka</a> philosophies and the <a href="/wiki/Praj%C3%B1%C4%81p%C4%81ramit%C4%81" class="mw-redirect" title="Praj\xc3\xb1\xc4\x81p\xc4\x81ramit\xc4\x81">Praj\xc3\xb1\xc4\x81p\xc4\x81ramit\xc4\x81</a> literature\xe2\x80\x94and of local traditions in China, particularly <a href="/wiki/Taoism" title="Taoism">Taoism</a> and Hu\xc3\xa1y\xc3\xa1n Buddhism. From China, Ch\xc3\xa1n subsequently spread southwards to <a href="/wiki/Buddhism_in_Vietnam" title="Buddhism in Vietnam">Vietnam</a> and eastwards to <a href="/wiki/Buddhism_in_Korea" class="mw-redirect" title="Buddhism in Korea">Korea</a> and <a href="/wiki/Buddhism_in_Japan" title="Buddhism in Japan">Japan</a>. In the late 19th and early 20th centuries, Zen also began to establish a notable presence in <a href="/wiki/North_America" title="North America">North America</a> and <a href="/wiki/Europe" title="Europe">Europe</a>.</p>\n<div class="noprint" style="margin:0.3em 0.2em 0.2em 0.3em; padding:0.3em 0.2em 0.2em 0.3em; text-align:right;"><b><a href="/wiki/Zen" title="Zen">Read more...</a></b></div>\n<div style="clear:both;"></div>\n</div>\n<div style="clear: both; border: solid #ed9121; border-width: 1px 1px 0; background: #ffec8b; color: #8B0000; padding: .1em;padding-top: .1em;padding-left: .1em;padding-right: .1em;padding-bottom: .1em;text-align: center;font-family: sans-serif;font-size:100%;margin-bottom: 0px;">\n<div class="plainlinks" style="float:right;margin-bottom:.1em;font-size:80%; color: #8B0000"><a class="external text" href="//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Portal:Mahayana_Buddhism/In_The_News&amp;action=edit"><span style="color: #8B0000">edit</span></a>&#160;&#160;</div>\n<h2 style="font-family:sans-serif; font-size:100%; font-weight:bold; border: none; margin: 0; padding:0; padding-bottom:.1em; color:#8B0000;"><span class="mw-headline" id="In_The_News">In The News</span></h2>\n</div>\n<div style="border: 1px solid #ed9121; border-top-width: 1px; vertical-align: top;background: #ffec8b;opacity: 1; color: black; text-align: left; margin: 0 0 10px; padding: 1em;padding-top: .3em;">\n<div class="floatleft"><a href="/wiki/File:Dalai_Lama_1430_Luca_Galuzzi_2007crop.jpg" class="image"><img alt="Dalai Lama 1430 Luca Galuzzi 2007crop.jpg" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/2d/Dalai_Lama_1430_Luca_Galuzzi_2007crop.jpg/100px-Dalai_Lama_1430_Luca_Galuzzi_2007crop.jpg" width="100" height="165" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/2d/Dalai_Lama_1430_Luca_Galuzzi_2007crop.jpg/150px-Dalai_Lama_1430_Luca_Galuzzi_2007crop.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/2d/Dalai_Lama_1430_Luca_Galuzzi_2007crop.jpg/200px-Dalai_Lama_1430_Luca_Galuzzi_2007crop.jpg 2x" data-file-width="748" data-file-height="1234" /></a></div>\n<ul>\n<li>This Sunday it was hoped <a href="/wiki/Tenzin_Gyatso" class="mw-redirect" title="Tenzin Gyatso">Tenzin Gyatso</a>, the <a href="/wiki/Dalai_Lama" title="Dalai Lama">Dalai Lama</a>, would preside over a mass conversion of Indian <a href="/wiki/Dalits" class="mw-redirect" title="Dalits">Dalits</a> to <a href="/wiki/Buddhism" title="Buddhism">Buddhism</a>. According to a report in <a href="/wiki/The_Hindu" title="The Hindu">The Hindu</a> newspaper he instead sent a message of encouragement to the mass conversion ceremony in <a href="/wiki/Mumbai" title="Mumbai">Mumbai</a>.</li>\n</ul>\n<ul>\n<li><a href="/wiki/Tenzin_Gyatso" class="mw-redirect" title="Tenzin Gyatso">Tenzin Gyatso</a>, the <a href="/wiki/14th_Dalai_Lama" title="14th Dalai Lama">14th Dalai Lama</a>, has vowed to step down from his position if things "get out of control" in <a href="/wiki/Tibet" title="Tibet">Tibet</a>, where violent demonstrations against <a href="/wiki/China" title="China">China</a> have killed anywhere from 13 to 100 people.</li>\n</ul>\n<div class="noprint" style="margin:0.3em 0.2em 0.2em 0.3em; padding:0.3em 0.2em 0.2em 0.3em; text-align:right;"></div>\n<div style="clear:both;"></div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</table>\n<div class="reflist" style="list-style-type: decimal;">\n<div class="mw-references-wrap">\n<ol class="references">\n<li id="cite_note-1"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-1">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">The world\'s earliest dated (868 AD) printed book is a Chinese scroll about sixteen feet long and containing the text of the <a href="/wiki/Diamond_Sutra" title="Diamond Sutra">Diamond Sutra</a>. It was found in 1907 by the <a href="/wiki/Archaeologist" class="mw-redirect" title="Archaeologist">archaeologist</a> Sir <a href="/wiki/Marc_Aurel_Stein" class="mw-redirect" title="Marc Aurel Stein">Marc Aurel Stein</a> in <a href="/wiki/Mogao_Caves" title="Mogao Caves">Mogao Caves</a> in <a href="/wiki/Dunhuang" title="Dunhuang">Dunhuang</a>, and is now in the <a href="/wiki/British_Museum" title="British Museum">British Museum</a>. The book displays a great maturity of design and layout and speaks of a considerable ancestry for woodblock printing. The <a href="/wiki/Colophon_(book)" class="mw-redirect" title="Colophon (book)">colophon</a>, at the inner end, reads: <i>Reverently [caused to be] made for universal free distribution by Wang Jie on behalf of his two parents on the 13th of the 4th moon of the 9th year of Xiantong [i.e. 11th May, CE 868 ]</i>.</span></li>\n</ol>\n</div>\n</div>\n<div class="hlist" style="text-align: center; clear:both; padding:0.25em 0 0.5em;">\n<ul>\n<li><b>What are <a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Portal" title="Wikipedia:Portal">portals</a>?</b></li>\n<li><b><a href="/wiki/Portal:Contents/Portals" title="Portal:Contents/Portals">List of portals</a></b></li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n<p><br /></p>\n</div>\n<table width="100%" cellpadding="5" cellspacing="10" style="background:#f5fffa; border-style:solid; border-width:1px; border-color:#cedff2;">\n<tr>\n<td></td>\n</tr>\n</table>\n\n\n<!-- \nNewPP limit report\nParsed by mw1267\nCached time: 20170809200213\nCache expiry: 1900800\nDynamic content: false\nCPU time usage: 0.124 seconds\nReal time usage: 0.188 seconds\nPreprocessor visited node count: 1522/1000000\nPreprocessor generated node count: 0/1500000\nPost\xe2\x80\x90expand include size: 60453/2097152 bytes\nTemplate argument size: 6329/2097152 bytes\nHighest expansion depth: 8/40\nExpensive parser function count: 0/500\nLua time usage: 0.016/10.000 seconds\nLua memory usage: 887 KB/50 MB\n-->\n<!--\nTransclusion expansion time report (%,ms,calls,template)\n100.00%  120.891      1 -total\n 38.70%   46.788      1 Portal:Mahayana_Buddhism/Selected_Mahayana_Buddhist\n 36.30%   43.884      1 Template:Dn\n 21.53%   26.032      1 Template:Fix\n 19.52%   23.602      2 Template:Category_handler\n 12.84%   15.517     12 Portal:Mahayana_Buddhism/box-header\n 10.02%   12.108     12 Template:Box-header\n  8.91%   10.768      1 Template:Reflist\n  7.15%    8.642      1 Portal:Mahayana_Buddhism/Header\n  6.62%    8.004      1 Template:Religion_browsebar\n-->\n</div>\n<!-- Saved in parser cache with key enwiki:pcache:idhash:16619834-0!canonical and timestamp 20170809200213 and revision id 649284765\n -->\n<noscript><img src="//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Special:CentralAutoLogin/start?type=1x1" alt="" title="" width="1" height="1" style="border: none; position: absolute;" /></noscript></div>\t\t\t\t\t<div class="printfooter">\n\t\t\t\t\t\tRetrieved from "<a dir="ltr" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Port